To convert markdown formatted text to HTML formatted text, you can use a library like `pandoc-cpp` which is a C++ port of the popular `pandoc` tool. First, you need to install the `pandoc-cpp` library. You can do this using a package manager like `apt` for Debian-based systems or `brew` for macOS.

For Debian-based systems:
```bash
sudo apt-get install pandoc-cpp
```

For macOS (using `brew`):
```bash
brew install pandoc-cpp
```

Once you have `pandoc-cpp` installed, you can create a C++ function that uses it to convert markdown to HTML. Here's an example implementation:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <pandoc-cpp/pandoc.h>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown_text) {
    pandoc::Document md;
    pandoc::Document html;

    pandoc::read_markdown(md, markdown_text);
    pandoc::write_html(html, pandoc::WriterOptions());

    std::string html_text;
    pandoc::write_string(html, html_text);

    return html_text;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "## Hello, World!\n\nThis is a simple markdown document.";
    std::string html = markdown_to_html(markdown);

    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code snippet includes the necessary headers, defines a function `markdown_to_html` that takes a `std::string` containing markdown text and returns a `std::string` containing the corresponding HTML text. The function uses `pandoc-cpp` to read the markdown text, convert it to HTML, and then return the HTML text.

In the `main` function, we provide a sample markdown text, call `markdown_to_html` with this text, and print the resulting HTML text.

Please note that you need to link against `pandoc-cpp` when compiling your program. For example, using `g++`:
```bash
g++ -o markdown_to_html markdown_to_html.cpp -lpandoc-cpp
```

This will create an executable named `markdown_to_html` that you can use to convert markdown to HTML.

