    // Load other images if needed
    // ...

    // Game loop setup
    // ...

    // Clean up
    // ...

    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    IMG_Quit();
    SDL_Quit();
    return 0;
}
```

### Step 7: Load and Display Images
Load your snake image using `SDL_LoadBMP` or `IMG_LoadPNG` and create a texture:
```c
snakeTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "snake.png");
```

### Step 8: Game Loop
Implement the game loop where you handle user input, update the snake's position, and render the game state:
```c
while (running) {
    SDL_Event event;
    while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
        if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) {
            running = false;
        }
    }

    // Update snake position
    // ...

    // Clear the screen
    SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

    // Render snake and other game elements
    SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snakeTexture, NULL, NULL);

    // Update the screen
    SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);
}
```

### Step 9: Handle Snake Movement and Collisions
Implement logic to handle snake movement, collision detection with the walls, and collision with food. Adjust the snake's position and score accordingly.

### Step 10: Add Game Over Logic
Implement a condition to end the game when the snake collides with the walls or itself.

### Step 11: Compile and Run Your Game
Compile your game using a command like:
```bash
gcc -o snake_game main.c -lSDL2 -lSDL2_image
```
Then run it with:
```bash
./snake_game
```

### Step 12: Debug and Improve
Debug your game, add sound effects, and improve the user interface and game mechanics.

